It is highly unlikely that the Worst Case Release Scenario or Alternative Release Scenarios will occur at the plant for the following reasons:
The chlorine process and process areas are inspected daily;
The chlorine containers and storage rooms are monitored 24-hours per day, 7-days per week, 365-days per year for process leaks via automatic leak detectors;
The leak detectors are considered critical equipment and thus are incorporated into the Mechanical Integrity Program. As such, each detector is well maintained and tested twice each month;
ALL chlorine storage, handling and use area entry doors are equipped with intruder alarms to guard against unauthorized entry and/or vandalism;
ALL one ton containers are inspected prior to acceptance and storage onsite;
ALL one-ton containers stored/managed onsite are secured in-place via two chain binders to prevent movement or dislodging due to seismic events; and
ALL Plant Operators and Members of the Emergency Response Team are trained to respond to- and stop- process leaks.

There are a number of detection and monitoring devices and alarms designed to ensure the continued safe operation of Water Reclamation Plant No. 7. These devices are located throughout the Plant and monitor various aspects of Plant Operations. 

Alarms
WRP No. 7 is equipped with Leak Detectors that are designed to detect chlorine in the chlorine storage area at or above 1-ppm. When one of these detectors senses a gas leak at or above 1-ppm, an audible alarm is indicated locally and on the annunciator panel in the onsite control room AND an alarm is transmitted to District Control at Headquarters AND the ventilation fan is automatically switched on and starts to evacuate the room.. At 3-ppm the beacon lights on top of the chlorine building are activated. These alarms can only be re
